Entry.22:
Sun 9th

This morning we went out mounted with B.Sqd. Sigs & put the morning in signalling with Helios; Les received a pass to town from dinner time & I put the afternoon in at the A.V.C. as the last snapshots of me were a failure I sat again; 

After tea Arthur Bottom & I went to Cairo; Morgan left Hospital at 3 oclock today; & he met us at Heliopolis & went in with us; We intended going to the Kursaal but found it filled & the doors shut, so we had supper at the Egyptian Cafe & then tea at the cake shop & then came home; We had geat fun in the tram , the compartment we were in had several Greeks & French & Bottom was at his best & caused plenty of amusement.

Entry.29:
Sun 16th

This morning the horses were taken off the line 3 horses per man, & the rest of us put up breast lines to picket the horses to & a rough job is was digging holes 4 feet deep in loose sand to put the posts in, but we had the lines ready at dinner time;

This afternoon we were issued witht the same tents that we had at Heliopolis & put them up; The transports & all baggage came by train; We were given our black kits tonight a few of these went astray probably with the 2nd Regt mine amongst them but hope to get it tomorrow; Water pipes have been laid down to troughs close by the horse lines & are very handy these were only completed this afternoon; It looks as though we are in for a dull, quiet time here

Entry.62:
Frid 18th

This morning Cpl Guthrie went in to Beni-Mazar with a party of 4 men to bring out more ammunition (52 cases) I had a very easy time at the well last night went to bed as soon as it was dark & never woke till sunrise;

A transport goes from here to B troop every , & they are having a very fair time by all accounts but fare no better than we do for tucker; Boxing after tea & then went to the canal with several other lads, & had a swim; The niggers selling, Egyptian cigarettes, matches, candles, & occasionally bread & jam charge terrible prices 1/- for a small loaf of bread; An Egyptian Officer has turned up a few times , & brought the prices down a little, but the natives send them up again as soon as they leave.

Entry.88:
Tue 14th

We have been told that no mail is to leave Egypt for 6 weeks on account of the movement of troops from here to France; The Interpeter is now camped in this tent. He is a Christian, also a young Egyptian who was in England studying for a Dr. when war broke out is here & seems a very decent fellow, he also is a Christian, & says that practically all the natives in this village are also Christians; 

Eleven bags of mail for the 1st Regt is at Tuk-El-Khul, I am doing a fair amount of work here at present, but it is not very labororous as it is all book work; The Col objected to Snow transferring to the Art. Amm. Column, the Col is always nasty in this respect, & does not like anyone to leave the Regt. even to better himself; 

Boxing is very popular every evening we make good use of the gloves

Entry.89:
Wed 15th

Davies who went ot Heliopolis with sick horses from Bahnasa arrived back here yesterday & says that nearly all our reinforcements have been transferred to the Ammunition Column & are to go to England. he said Stan is also trying to transfer, but was told that no Signallers would be taken.

Received orders at dinner time to go onto a hill in the desert about 3 miles from here & try to pick up the signalling station at Minia with the helio. The trumpeters took over the phone work. We had an enjoyable ride through the cultivated fields (Reid & I) & had no trouble in getting in touch with Minia about 10 miles away & arrived back in camp to find a mail had arrived for us, also a parcel of Cocoa & milk from Stan;

Entry.91:
Fri 17th

Was out on the desert again today. but Minia was the only station we could get into communication with; The Colonel came down today & the 3 men who were the cause of the disturbance in the village a few nights ago were up before him but discharged;

Had tea with our native friends at the village on the edge of the desert when coming back to camp; 3 camels were sighted on the desert West of Nazlet-El-Abid this afternoon but they made off back into the desert when the patrol tried to approach them, & special patrols are being sent out from all villages where troops are stationed tonight in the hopes of catching them; 

Boxing still booms every evening after tea.

Entry.92:
Sat 18th

This morning there was a crowd of natives with donkeys, goats, sheep, fowls etc waiting to cross the river on the punt when we were going out this morning apparently making into a small village close by us to a fare;

Had tea again with out friend Abdul Hamid when going onto the desert this morning & promised to call again this afternoon, but as we went a couple of miles towards Tuk-El-Khul at dinner time in hopes of getting on higher ground (without success) we came into the village a different way & did not call on him; It was windy today & very unpleasant on the desert with the fine sand blowing all over us; I am trying to raise the energy necessary to learn Arabic; Fleas are very troublesome here
